        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The review of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2241.xml"><hi rend="italic">Earthworms</hi></ref> appeared in the <hi rend="italic">Athenæum</hi>, 15 October 1881, pp. 499–500; the author was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2814.xml">Edwin Ray Lankester</ref> (City University of London archives, annotated copy of the <hi rend="italic">Athenæum</hi>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2241.xml"><hi rend="italic">Earthworms</hi></ref>, pp. 66–8, CD discussed the worms’ habit of drawing leaves into burrows by the apex or tip. He noted that worms sometimes lay in contact and crawled over each other (<hi rend="italic">Earthworms</hi>, p. 35), but he did not describe them working together to draw in leaves.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The review described CD’s method as the ‘summing-up of the effects of a continually recurrent cause. No matter how small the cause, Mr. Darwin has shown ... that the continuity of nature allows vast effects to result from their operation’ (<hi rend="italic">Athenæum</hi>, 15 October 1881, p. 500).</note>
            
